      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implement exponential backoff for retries to avoid overwhelming the API during outages. Always validate responses for HTTP status codes and parse JSON errors systematically."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementing Efficient Request Handling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To minimize latency, batch multiple inference requests where possible, but respect API rate limits. Use asynchronous programming (e.g., async/await in Python or JavaScript) to handle concurrent requests without blocking. Cache frequent responses with a TTL based on use-case volatility, and compress payloads if the API supports it. Monitor request sizes to stay within payload limits and avoid unnecessary data transfer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Managing API Responses and Errors"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Design your error handling to distinguish between client-side issues (e.g., invalid parameters) and server-side failures. Log detailed error messages with timestamps and request IDs for debugging. Implement circuit breakers to halt requests temporarily if error rates spike, and set up alerts for critical failures. For rate limiting, parse the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Retry-After",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " header and queue requests accordingly to maintain throughput."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scaling and Performance Tuning"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scale horizontally by distributing requests across multiple API keys or endpoints if permitted. Use load balancers to manage traffic and ensure high availability. Profile API response times regularly and adjust client-side concurrency based on latency metrics. Consider deploying a proxy layer to cache common requests and reduce direct API calls, but ensure cache invalidation aligns with model updates."
          }
        ]
      }
